          "body": "The climax of Leviticus 24 is not the blasphemy verdict but the declaration of v. 22: 'There shall be one standard for you; it shall be for the stranger as well as the native, for I am the LORD your God.' The mishpat echad (one standard of judgment) is the chapter's most radical social claim. In the ancient world, resident aliens had diminished legal standing — they were tolerated guests, not full legal persons. Israel's law abolishes that distinction before the LORD's court. The alien (ger) who blaspemes faces the same death penalty as the native Israelite (v. 16); the alien who murders faces the same capital verdict (v. 22). The ground of the equal standard is not humanitarian sentiment but the character of the LORD Himself: 'for I am the LORD your God.' The same formula that grounds Israel's entire Holiness Code (repeated throughout chapters 17-26) here anchors equal justice. God's impartiality is not a democratic principle borrowed from political philosophy; it is an attribute of the God before whom the lampstand burns without ceasing and before whom every human nephesh stands with equal weight."
