          "title": "Obedience completed — the community executes the verdict",
          "body": "Verse 23 closes the chapter with the compliance formula characteristic of Leviticus: 'the sons of Israel did, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' This is not a casual narrative conclusion. It frames the entire chapter as a demonstration that Israel's community is capable of receiving God's law in a crisis and executing it completely. The man who blasphemed the Name is taken outside the camp — expelled from the space where the lampstand burns and the showbread is set weekly — and stoned. The community that heard his blasphemy participates in the execution; they are both witnesses and agents of the verdict. The chapter began with the LORD commanding perpetual honor of His Name in the sanctuary and ends with the community actively defending that honor in the camp. Both acts — tending the lampstand and executing the blasphemer — are obedience. Both are ways of declaring that the Name of the LORD is not to be made light of, in the sanctuary or in the streets."
