        "title": "The blasphemy crisis — a case that generates law",
        "range": "24:10-14",
        "excerpt": "They put him in custody so that the command of the LORD might be made clear to them.",
        "body": "The narrative intrusion of vv. 10-14 is one of a small number of legal narratives in the Pentateuch where a specific incident becomes the occasion for divine legislation (cf. Numbers 9:6-14; 15:32-36; 27:1-11; 36:1-12). The pattern is consistent: an unprecedented situation arises, the community correctly suspends judgment pending divine clarification, and the LORD issues a ruling that becomes permanently binding. Leviticus 24 follows this pattern exactly.\n\nThe man's identity is carefully given: son of an Israelite woman and an Egyptian father (v. 10). The detail is not ethnographically incidental — it signals his ambiguous covenant status. He is among the 'sons of Israel' (v. 10) but is not straightforwardly one of them. The quarrel in the camp (natsah, v. 10 — a violent dispute) escalates until the man blasphemes the Name and curses. The Hebrew construction in v. 11 is striking: naqav ha-shem veqalal — 'he pierced the Name and made it light.' Two verbs, both devastating. To pierce (naqav) the Name is to wound or puncture what is most sacred; to curse (qalal) is to assign minimum weight to what has infinite weight.\n\nThe community's response is exemplary: they bring him to Moses and hold him in custody (v. 12). They do not improvise a verdict. They recognize that the law they have received from Sinai (Exodus 20:7 — 'You shall not take the Name of the LORD your God in vain') does not specify the penalty for this degree of offense, and they correctly wait for the LORD to speak. Verse 12 is a model of judicial restraint under divine law: the community knows what it does not know, and it waits for the commanding voice rather than filling the gap with human invention.\n\nThe LORD's answer comes in vv. 13-14 with striking specificity: bring the blasphemer outside the camp, let all who heard lay their hands on his head, then let the whole congregation stone him. The hand-laying ritual (samakh et-yad, v. 14) is the same gesture used in the sacrificial system (Leviticus 1:4; 3:2; 4:4) where the offerer lays hands on the animal before it is slaughtered, identifying himself with the offering. Here the witnesses lay hands on the offender's head — transferring back to him the guilt his words placed on them as hearers, and identifying him as the one who must bear the full weight of the defilement.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Naqav* (blaspheme, v. 11) literally means to pierce or bore through — the word used for engraving or piercing precious stones (Exodus 28:9). Applied to the Name, it conveys the sense of treating what is most hallowed with destructive contempt. *Qalal* (curse, v. 11) is the polar opposite of *kaved* (to honor, to make heavy) — to qalal someone is to treat them as featherweight. *Samakh yad* (lay the hand on, v. 14) — the sacrificial gesture of identification and transference, applied here to communal guilt-removal."
