        "title": "The Name inviolable — blasphemy and its universal application",
        "range": "24:15-16",
        "excerpt": "The alien as well as the native, when he blasphemes the Name, shall be put to death.",
        "body": "Verses 15-16 move from the particular verdict (the one man) to the universal principle (everyone). The shift is signaled grammatically: 'You shall speak to the sons of Israel, saying' (v. 15) — the case has generated permanent law that must be announced to the whole community. Two levels of the offense are distinguished. Verse 15 addresses the lighter form: 'If anyone curses his God (elohim), he will bear his sin.' The indefinite elohim leaves open the possibility of a non-Israelite who curses a generic deity — he is held accountable (nasa chet, he will carry his sin as a burden) but the penalty is not specified as capital. This may indicate a lesser charge for those who do not yet know the covenant Name.\n\nVerse 16 escalates to the capital offense: 'Moreover, the one who blasphemes the name of the LORD (YHWH) shall surely be put to death.' The verb mut appears in the absolute infinitive construction (mot yumat) — the doubled form meaning 'shall surely, certainly, without exception be put to death.' This is the Torah's strongest formulation of capital penalty. And the verse does double duty: it opens and closes with the death verdict, sandwiching the extension to alien and native between the two statements of penalty. The legal structure insists that the foreigner resident in Israel faces the same charge and the same outcome.\n\nThe theological reason for the severity is not judicial severity for its own sake. The Name of YHWH is not simply a label by which God is identified. In the Semitic world a name carries the person — to know, speak, and honor the Name is to relate rightly to the person whose Name it is. YHWH's Name is the concentrated expression of His character, His covenant commitments, His acts in history, and His self-disclosure. To blaspheme the Name is not a speech offense; it is an assault on the person and being of God. Calvin observed: 'God connects the safety of His glory with the holy reverence of His name... the Name represents all that God is.' The death penalty is proportional not to the noise of the words but to the weight of what the words attack.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Naqav ha-shem YHWH* — 'blasphemes the Name of YHWH.' The definite article on shem (the Name) in v. 16 signals that YHWH's covenant Name is in view specifically, not a generic deity. *Mot yumat* — the cognate accusative construction (infinite absolute + finite verb) expressing the strongest possible verbal assertion: 'dying he shall die,' rendered 'shall surely be put to death.' *Ger* (alien/foreigner) and *ezrach* (native-born) — the pairing that defines the chapter's one-law principle, appearing also in Exodus 12:48-49 and Numbers 9:14."
